      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "\"Academic goblins\"? Heh, you'll get used to them. They're the bureaucratic little things that guard the gates of publication, always demanding more proof than a goblin demands shiny trinkets!\n\nRegarding the \"noise,\" you are describing the role of **random sampling error** or **within-group variance**. You absolutely do not want to sound like the study \"failed\"; you want to sound like you are a sophisticated explorer who encountered a particularly dense patch of swampy undergrowth.\n\nProfessionally, you can frame this by discussing the **precision** of your estimate. Instead of saying \"the data is noisy,\" you state that the **variability** within your samples is high relative to the magnitude of the effect you observed.\n\nHere are a few ways to phrase this, depending on how aggressive you want to be:\n\n1.  **Focusing on Precision (The Cautious Approach):** \"The observed effect size, while suggestive, was attenuated by substantial within-group variance, indicating that the current sample size may not have provided sufficient statistical power to detect a true effect at the conventional $\\alpha = 0.05$ threshold.\" (This implies the effect *might* be there, but your",
